      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Preserve Our Culture, Byte by Byte</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>John Bryant letter on electronic books to be used by new generation of scholars (Oct 21 editorial)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Scholarly Editions in Jeopardy'' (editorial, Oct. 21):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Scholarly Editions in Jeopardy'' (editorial, Oct. 21):</p>
        <p>Cuts in financing for the National Endowment for the Humanities over the last decade have had a devastating effect on scholarly projects that preserve and extend to Americans the writings of their culture.</p>
        <p>We are looking now to a new era of electronic editing, and a new generation of scholars are eager to devise new approaches to editing that will make more and different kinds of texts available.</p>
        <p>A scholarly electronic edition can give readers immediate access to the sources of texts and display them side by side with the texts themselves, thereby illuminating the reading experience. An electronic edition can display all versions in ways not possible in books and walk readers through the paths of revision a writer may have taken, or show the way a text has been censored, bowdlerized or adapted.</p>
        <p>Where will this new generation of scholars get money for their new electronic editions?</p>
        <p>JOHN BRYANT  Scarsdale, N.Y., Oct. 24, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of English at Hofstra University.</p>
      </block>
